r doesn’t include $, and since class attributes are NMTOKEN, it looks like the $ symbol is invalid. I think I should create public helper classes to maintain a one-to-one mapping with test classes.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Java file structure**\\n\\nI'm thinking about organizing my Java files under src/test/java. Should I avoid extra public helper files? I could create public static nested helper classes inside a public test file, but there's the issue with the $ symbol in class attributes like `org_mortbay_jetty.jetty.XmlConfigurationTest$ConfigurableBean`, which might violate NMTOKEN rules. I wonder if I can bypass the DTD. I really should inspect the XmlParser to understand its validation better.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_MGyZ1KkU1cxk2fL0PmMkGeer|fc_0c3a5c965fd6145c0169ff0c6bc398819682579438c6b78838", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "../../source_context/org.mortbay.jetty/jetty/6.1.26/main/extracted/org/mortbay/xml/XmlParser.java", "offset": 1, "limit": 260}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2561, "output": 845, "cacheRead": 18432, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 21838, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778322522861, "responseId": "resp_0c3a5c965fd6145c0169ff0c5b595081969be9aa1af1b1886a"}}
